               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1355" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1355" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1355" type="surname" value="LINO"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1355" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN LINO</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to William Nathan, a pawnbroker, in Three Colt-street, Limehouse. I missed a pair of trowsers from the door, and went to Ratcliff-highway—I saw the prisoner in company with two other persons—the prisoner separated from them—I followed him till I met an officer, and then gave him in charge—he was searched at the sta<lb></lb>tion-house, and the trowsers found secreted under his coat, round his body—he said he bought them in Rosemary-lane—I had seen them sale at two o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390204-name-1356" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1356" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1356" type="surname" value="JACKSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390204-name-1356" type="given" value="LOWTHER"></interp>LOWTHER JACKSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tailor, and live in Three Colt-street On the 7th of February, about six o'clock, I saw the prisoner with two others pass my door—the prisoner looked into my shop—I went to the door, and they got to Nathan's, which is two doors from me—I went in-doors, and sent my son to inform Mr. Nathan that suspicious characters were at his door, and when I got back to the door they were gone—they were fol<lb></lb>lowed, and the prisoner was taken,</p>
               <p>
